# Comparative map

| Coalition      | Dominant masculine priority | Dominant feminine priority | Governing direction         | Aggregate archetype |
| -------------- | --------------------------- | -------------------------- | --------------------------- | ------------------- |
| **Republican** | Dignity                     | Recognition                | Dignity governs recognition | **King**            |
| **Democratic** | Security                    | Harmony                    | Harmony governs security    | **Mother**          |

The broader aggregate orientation is:

| Republican coalition      | Democratic coalition     |
| ------------------------- | ------------------------ |
| Dignity                   | Harmony                  |
| Security                  | Comfort                  |
| Acquisition               | Recognition              |
| Masculine-column dominant | Feminine-column dominant |

Within PBMM’s symbolic language, the Republican coalition is more strongly **masculine-coded**, while the Democratic coalition is more strongly **feminine-coded**.

This does not refer to the biological sex of voters. It describes which column of the priority matrix receives greater aggregate emphasis.

## The same issue through different masks

| Issue          | Republican reading                         | Democratic reading                                    |
| -------------- | ------------------------------------------ | ----------------------------------------------------- |
| Immigration    | Security, dignity, sovereignty             | Harmony, recognition, humane comfort                  |
| Economy        | Acquisition, security, independence        | Comfort, harmony, equal opportunity                   |
| Health care    | Choice, acquisition, personal control      | Comfort, security, collective provision               |
| Crime          | Security, boundaries, deterrence           | Security through harmony, prevention, and reform      |
| Free speech    | Dignity and resistance to control          | Recognition and protection from social harm           |
| Welfare        | Possible threat to acquisition and dignity | Comfort and security supporting harmony               |
| Taxation       | Control of acquired resources              | Distribution of resources toward comfort and cohesion |
| Foreign policy | Dignity, leverage, deterrence              | Harmony, diplomacy, collective security               |
| Environment    | Acquisition balanced against security      | Security, comfort, and intergenerational harmony      |

The parties often talk past one another because they are not merely proposing different solutions. They are noticing different classes of failure.

The Republican coalition asks:

> Can the country defend itself, maintain sovereignty, and continue producing?

The Democratic coalition asks:

> Can people live within the country safely, humanely, and with recognized membership?

Both questions are necessary.

