# Coalition subtypes

Neither party is internally uniform.

Pew’s 2026 typology identifies several distinct right-leaning and left-leaning groups. Some Republican-oriented groups are strongly ideological and culturally conservative, while others are more moderate, civil, or unconventional. Democratic-oriented groups range from institutional liberals to younger progressives, economically stressed voters, and people who combine liberal economic preferences with greater concern about crime or immigration. ([Pew Research Center][1])

PBMM could map these factions separately.

For example:

* A hard-right faction may be heavily King and Guardian.
* A business-oriented Republican faction may be more Pioneer or Builder.
* A civil, institution-oriented Republican faction may include the Gentleman or Steward.
* A progressive Democratic faction may emphasize Queen, Mother, and Trickster.
* A working-class Democratic faction may be more Hearthkeeper and Guardian.
* An institutional liberal faction may combine Mother, Weaver, and Steward.

The party-level map is therefore a center of gravity, not a complete description.

---

# What the comparison reveals

The model offers a neutral interpretation of polarization.

Republicans are not simply people who “do not care.” Their coalition is more attentive to sovereignty, boundaries, strength, production, and resistance to degradation.

Democrats are not simply people who “want comfort.” Their coalition is more attentive to relational cohesion, recognition, vulnerability, and whether resources are converted into livable conditions.

Each coalition monitors failures the other can neglect.

The masculine column asks:

> Can the system establish itself, defend itself, and obtain what it needs?

The feminine column asks:

> Is value properly recognized, is the social field coherent, and is life within the system worth living?

Political dysfunction intensifies when either coalition treats its own priorities as morality itself and interprets the opposite column as stupidity, weakness, cruelty, or corruption.

---

# Limits of the analysis

This document analyzes party rhetoric and aggregate coalition behavior. It does not establish the hidden motives of individual Republicans or Democrats.

Political positions can arise from:

* personal experience,
* regional interests,
* religion,
* class,
* occupation,
* identity,
* institutional incentives,
* strategic calculation,
* or disagreement about facts.

A policy may also serve several priorities simultaneously.

PBMM should therefore be used to generate hypotheses such as:

> This argument appears to prioritize security over harmony.

It should not be used to make categorical claims such as:

> Republicans do not value harmony.

> Democrats do not value dignity.

Every coalition contains all six priorities. The distinction lies in their relative weighting, symbolic emphasis, and willingness to sacrifice one priority for another.

The purpose of the model is not to erase political disagreement.

It is to make the motivational structure beneath that disagreement more intelligible.

